               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1318" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1318" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1318" type="surname" value="BILL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1318" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BILL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Richard Moser, senior, and another, iron<lb></lb>merchants,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184201310188"></xptr>
               <p>No. 165, Borough. I know the prisoner, he has come to our firm three or four times for steel—on the 12th of January I saw him there—it is my duty to make out the invoices, which I did for these goods—I do not know that the prisoner spoke to me—he presented me with a written order for the goods now produced—he said nothing—be<lb></lb>lieving it to be genuine, I made out a bill for two bundles of spring-steel, 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I do not remember his saying any thing—he took the steel away—he had had goods before—not on his own account.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I did not have the steel, and never made out the order—I was on board a steam-boat at the time. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I am sure he is the man, I know he went away with the steel—I cannot recollect whether he took it on his shoulder or in a truck—he must have had a truck, it weighed 2cwt. lqr.—I am certain he is the man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1319" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1319" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1319" type="surname" value="DRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1319" type="given" value="JEMIMA"></interp>JEMIMA DRY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and carry on the business of a wheel<lb></lb>wright and smith, in Horse and Groom-yard, Westminster. The prisoner was in my employ five years ago, as hammerman to his father, who worked for me—I have not seen him since—he was discharged five years ago—I dealt with Messrs. Moser then, and do so now—this order is not my writing—I never authorised any body to write it for me, and none of the goods ever came to my premises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420131-name-1320" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1320" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1320" type="surname" value="MORRISS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420131-name-1320" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM MORRISS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am porter to Moser and Son. I know the pri<lb></lb>soner, and have seen him at our premises more than three times—I can<lb></lb>not state the date, but I have seen him twice since Christmas—I delivered some steel to him on a Tuesday, the last time he came, but I know no<lb></lb>thing about the order now produced—it was another order—I cannot recollect the transaction of the 12th of January—I know nothing of the delivery of these goods myself—we have no other customer named Dry—(<hi rend="italic">order read</hi>)—"12th January, 1842. Please let the bearer hare two bundles of spring steel.—J. <hi rend="smallCaps">DRY</hi>."</p>
